1. Problem Statement

The Low Autocorrelation Binary Sequence (LABS) problem is a combinatorial optimization task with applications in radar, communications, and signal processing. Classical solvers such as Memetic Tabu Search (MTS) achieve strong performance but still exhibit exponential scaling, making large problem sizes computationally expensive.

Near-term quantum devices cannot yet solve LABS end-to-end due to:

Limited qubit counts

Noise

Circuit depth constraints

There is a need for a hybrid quantum‚Äìclassical approach that provides practical, near-term performance gains without requiring fault-tolerant quantum hardware.

2. Product Vision

Use quantum computation as a structured global sampler to generate high-quality candidate solutions, which are then refined classically using MTS.

The quantum component does not replace classical optimization ‚Äî it enhances it.

3. Goals & Success Metrics
Primary Goals

Improve convergence speed of classical MTS

Bias search toward low-energy LABS configurations

Maintain validity of all generated solutions

Success Metrics

Lower LABS energy compared to random initialization

Reduced MTS iterations to reach comparable solutions

Stable execution on NISQ-era simulators / hardware

Correct mapping from LABS Hamiltonian ‚Üí quantum circuit

4. Target Users

Quantum computing researchers

Optimization researchers

Hackathon participants

CUDA-Q users exploring hybrid workflows

5. Functional Requirements
FR-1: LABS Hamiltonian Construction

Convert LABS cost function into an Ising Hamiltonian

Support arbitrary sequence length 
